                                alt="Point-shaving over the years: Several college sports scandals have been the result of athletes point-shaving. One of the biggest point-shaving schemes ever came in 1979 when four Boston College hoops players were involved in fixing nine games. Another noteworthy point-shaving scheme was one of the first in the 1950s, when the City College of New York (CCNY) won both the NIT and NCAA basketball championships, and it was revealed a year later that seven players conspired to shave points and seven schools in all were involved. Other schools caught with point-shaving over the years included Kentucky (1950s and 1980s), Northwestern (1994) and Arizona State (1994)." data-id=""><meta itemprop="height" content="510" /><meta itemprop="width" content="680" /><div class="gallery-viewport-meta meta"><div itemprop="caption" class="caption gallery-viewport-caption">
                                Point-shaving over the years: Several college sports scandals have been the result of athletes point-shaving. One of the biggest point-shaving schemes ever came in 1979 when four Boston College hoops players were involved in fixing nine games. Another noteworthy point-shaving scheme was one of the first in the 1950s, when the City College of New York (CCNY) won both the NIT and NCAA basketball championships, and it was revealed a year later that seven players conspired to shave points and seven schools in all were involved. Other schools caught with point-shaving over the years included Kentucky (1950s and 1980s), Northwestern (1994) and Arizona State (1994).&#160;
