n&#39;s basketball team in April after video footage of him physically and verbally abusing his players was aired. Rutgers AD Tim Pernetti had viewed the tape and only suspended Rice three games and fine him $75,000. Julie Hermann replaced Pernetti as the school&#39;s athletic director and Eddie Jordan is now the program&#39;s coach." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/ffec4319e84fe06d0d21f5547ee8396966a7dc3b/c=185-48-3387-1862&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/13/1379079928000-USATSI-7188152.jpg" alt="Notre Dame football (2013): Irish linebacker Manti Te&#39;o finished second in the Heisman voting. It was revealed that Lennay Kekua, Te&#39;o&#39;s supposed girlfriend, never existed. Notre Dame defended Te&#39;o, saying he was tricked and the program knew of the hoax since Dec. 26." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/ce84a1c720597b265042582ef01d6977b4875702/c=187-204-4213-2482&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/13/1379080147000-USATSI-6157546.jpg" alt="Arkansas football (2012): Former coach Bobby Petrino was hurt in a motorcycle accident in which he said he was alone but it was later discovered that Jessica Dorrell, a former Razorbacks volleyball player, was with Petrino and he had an extramatrital affair. Petrino was fired, and now coaches at Western Kentucky." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/e57cb2bb5f6084744bb36de8a97ad6b46956b719/c=170-50-2390-1308&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/10/1378846395000-PATERNO-SANDUSKY.jpg" alt="Penn State football (2011): The school&#39;s sex abuse scandal shook the nation, as former assistant coach Jerry Sandusky was indicted in 2011 on 52 counts of child molestation dating from 1994 to 2009. While Sandusky maintained his innocence, school president Graham Spanier was forced to resign, and the legendary Joe Paterno was fired, along with AD Tim Curley. On July 23, 2012 the NCAA imposed sweeping penalties on Penn State&#39;s football program&amp;mdash;among the most severe ever imposed on an NCAA member school&amp;mdash;including a fine of $60 million, a four-year postseason ban and vacating of all victories from 1998&amp;ndash;2011." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/ad0df9d660d9f7009096a8e687c935d810e50f8b/c=0-123-2660-1631&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/12/1379026655000-USP-NCAA-Football-North-Carolina-State-at-Miami.jpg" alt="Miami football (2011): In the latest scandal to hit the program, 73 former Hurricanes football players were implicated. Booster Nevin Shapiro, subsequently jailed for running a pyramid scheme, allegedly dispensed money, prostitutes, cars and vacations to the players. Shapiro said coaches and university officials knew of his gifts. In the 1980s, Luther Campbell was alleged to have been behind what was referred to as a &quot;pay-for-play&quot; system, which involved cash rewards for acts such as scoring touchdowns and big hits." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/3daa99a5092494c33783131b7aa0997f28e2268c/c=0-25-1782-1030&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/10/1378850436000-OHIO-STATE.jpg" alt="Ohio State football (2011): Coach Jim Tressel resigned after the NCAA found he knew and failed to report on a tattoos-for-jerseys deal with his players. That was followed by perhaps an even bigger scandal at the University of Miami in which jailed ex-booster Nevin Shapiro claimed he gave $2 million in benefits to 72 student-athletes." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/4c30df1d98e2f8dba4d432a00331ae21427176f8/c=0-79-3599-2109&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/12/1379021265000-c03-update-30.jpg" alt="Virginia lacrosse (2010): George Huguely was a midfielder for the Virginia Cavaliers men&#39;s lacrosse team. Huguely was found guilty for the murder of UVa women&#39;s lacrosse player Yeardley Love." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/838ae6457225ca4c8fb91cf6bdf03461e48187da/c=0-137-3108-1894&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/12/1379022409000-A12-EDIT-12.jpg" alt="Duke lacrosse (2006): Duke’s lacrosse team made national headlines after an exotic dancer accused three players of rape. On April 11, 2007, North Carolina Attorney General Roy Cooper dropped the case against Reade Seligman, Collin Finnerty and David Evans." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/d6eb72b2ea62ae052f2f9a2c97f8e267987894d3/c=0-31-1712-994&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/10/1378850754000-c01-bush-02.jpg" alt="USC football (2005): The Trojans were dealt a two year postseason ban and the loss of 30 scholarships over three years by the NCAA after it was reported that star running back Reggie Bush’s parents received hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash and gifts including a house in Malibu. Bush surrendered his 2005 Heisman trophy." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/f8a4d9acdf923d924e8b83272c4d8d30dc5a5706/c=151-18-1764-945&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/10/1378859686000-c01-barnett-09.jpg" alt="Colorado football (2004): Colorado was accused of using sex and alcohol to lure recruits to the school after several women reported they were sexually assaulted at parties. Katie Hnida, a former kicker, also said she was raped while on the team." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/26a2508edbaf626d92fb6ee8d52a749103b4d4aa/c=50-48-1590-1098&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/10/1378859461000-AP-PLAYER-DEATH.jpg" alt="Baylor basketball (2003): One of the saddest scandals ever broke out when Carlton Dotson murdered teammate Patrick Dennehy. It was later revealed that coach Dave Bliss was paying Dennehy&#39;s tuition and attempted to cover it up by portraying Dennehy as a drug dealer." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/907180e28063a742effa78dbdc48ccffb22db14d/c=100-105-1358-815&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/12/1379020258000-c10-cnotes-13.jpg" alt="St. Bonaventure basketball (2003): Jamil Terell became a student at St. Bonaventure in March of 2002 but only earned a welding certificate from Coastal Georgia Community College and had no associates degree. After the news broke, school president Robert Wickenheiser resigned, board president Bill Swan later committed suicide and the Bonnies were postseason play in 2003. Van Breda Kolff was later exonerated of any wrongdoing." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/11331e10d9cff85ddfcd573be89ec12c1dbaf73e/c=0-195-1510-1166&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/12/1379026168000-AP-HARRICK-JR.jpg" alt="Georgia basketball (2001): Former head coach Jim Harrick and his son, Jim Jr., were caught paying players&#39; expenses and provided higher grades to players in classes they rarely attended. The elder Harrick resigned and his son was fired in 2002." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/0b49f1bdd778dc3c12376548a62cebcc8d38d187/c=109-49-1529-851&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/12/1379019642000-AP-IB01-SLINE-15-MINNESOTA-HASKINS.jpg" alt="Minnesota basketball (1999): It was revealed that Minnesota basketball coach committed major academic fraud for several years during his tenure. Former academic adviser Jan Gangelhoff admitted to writing over 400 papers for at least 20 players. In turn, the Golden Gophers eventually forfeited postseason wins between 1993 and 1998. That included the school&#39;s Final Four appearance in 1997. Haskins lost his job in light of the scandal and also was dealt a seven year show-cause penalty." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/e6bfb7577df2dc75a737885206d5ec305b81b1ee/c=147-36-2918-1605&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/10/1378859250000-XXX-Fab-Five-Film-Basketball-Jimmy-King--Juwan-Howard--Chris-We.jpg" alt="Michigan basketball (1990s): The &quot;Fab Five&quot; were known for revolutionizing college hoops. It was uncovered that booster Ed Martin had given large amounts of cash away, and the school eventually vacated five seasons and all its hardware." width="80px" height="45px"></a></li><li class="thumb-item "><a href="#" class='thumb-link'><img class="thumb-image" src="http://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/c4a8058e8c3f5be5c8e49cee15b7632ff4ffa33e/c=41-8-431-230&amp;r=x48&amp;c=80x45/local/-/media/USATODAY/USATODAY/2013/09/10/1378847934000-5441e